observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation with modifications, and Management agreed to require the OMA to:
Conduct extensive retrieval of all documents pertaining to prior years’ records in order to determine the nature and composition of the book reconciling items;
Take up all valid reconciling items by preparing JEV duly supported with proper documentation and furnish the AT with copies of the same;
Trace all records to determine the validity of the long outstanding DIT and thereafter, communicate and make representations with the AGDBs to properly reflect the transactions or make the necessary adjusting entries in the books in case of errors, whichever is applicable;
Revert the amount of all the stale checks back to the CIB account of the Municipality and recognize the corresponding liability account or the government equity account whichever is applicable; and
Prepare and submit timely the BRS for all bank accounts of the MGM; and ensure that the submitted BRS are supported with the BS, DM/CMs and other supporting schedules/documents.
We also recommended and the MT agreed to refrain from charging to the GF the annual deposits being made to the three LBP accounts.

We reiterated our recommendations with modifications, and Management agreed to:
Discontinue the grant of CA to AOs with unliquidated CAs and designate another qualified bonded official/employee for the purpose in compliance with the applicable rules and regulations;
Compel the concerned accountable officials and employees who are still connected with the LGU to liquidate/settle their prior years’ CAs immediately, either by liquidation, payment or through salary deductions;
Exert extra effort to locate the necessary supporting documents relative to the long outstanding CAs and require those officials and employees who are already separated from the service to settle/liquidate their outstanding obligations by sending demand letters. Copy of the said demand letters bearing the receipts of the concerned accountable officials/employees should be furnished the AT; and
File a request for authority to write-off dormant unliquidated CAs and ensure compliance with the documentary requirements and forms prescribed in COA Circular No. 2023-008 for CAs of former officials and employees who are already deceased or cannot be located wherein the settlement/collectability of the same is unlikely, and henceforth strictly adhere with the governing law, rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of CAs.

We reiterated our previous recommendation and Management agreed to require the OMA to:
Conduct an extensive analysis and trace the details pertaining to the abnormal and non-moving balances to determine the appropriate actions needed and to present the correct balances of the affected accounts;
Make necessary representation with the GSIS and PhilHealth and other concerned offices to exhaust all efforts to locate the relevant documents to support the non-moving accounts, and thereafter, make the necessary adjustments in the books, if necessary;
Determine the existence of actual cash back-up of these accounts, thereafter, consider the settlement of the liabilities with the concerned agencies; and
Obtain a formal or written confirmation duly signed by the HDMF authorities, stating that the MGM has no outstanding payables to Pag-IBIG, to support the correcting entries to be made on the non-moving accounts.

10.14 	We recommended and the Management agreed that:
10.14.1 The Inspectorate Committee complete the physical inventory in three months or less and coordinate with the Municipal General Services Office (MGSO) in the preparation of a Physical Inventory Plan (PIP), in accordance with COA Circular             No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to facilitate the conduct of the required annual physical count of PPE in compliance with COA Circular No. 2002-003 dated June 20, 2002 and to address the unreconciled balances between the Accounting Office and MGSO;
The MGSO coordinate with the Accounting Office to determine the items to be included in the RPCPPE and with the Inspectorate Committee on the details and other relevant information to ensure the proper accomplishment of the RPCPPE based on the guidelines provided under COA Circular Nos. 2002-003 dated June 20, 2002 and 2020-006 dated     January 31, 2020;
The MGSO maintain the required Property Cards or its equivalent to record all acquisitions, depreciations, disposals and other information about the PPE to facilitate the reconciliation of any noted discrepancy between the records of the Accounting and the General Services Offices;
The Municipality facilitate the application of a one-time cleansing of PPE accounts in accordance with COA Circular    No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and
The Municipality consider increasing the number of personnel in the Accounting Office and in the MGSO to address the manpower constraints in the said Office and facilitate the maintenance of the required property records.

3.16 	We recommended and Management agreed to:
Create an Inspectorate Committee with adequate number of members to be able to complete the physical inventory in three months or less, who will coordinate with the Municipal General Services Office (MGSO) in the preparation of a Physical Inventory Plan (PIP), in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to promote the conduct of the required annual physical count of PPE in compliance with COA Circular             No. 2002-003 dated June 20, 2002 and to address the unreconciled balances between the Accounting Office and MGSO caused by non-existing/missing PPEs without available record of accountability;
Require the MGSO to coordinate with the Accounting Office to determine the items to be included in the RPCPPE and with the Inspectorate Committee on the details and other relevant information to ensure the proper accomplishment of the RPCPPE based on the guidelines provided under COA Circular               Nos. 2002-003 dated June 20, 2002 and 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
Require the Accounting Office and MGSO to maintain the required Property Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC) and Property Cards, respectively, or its equivalent to record all acquisitions, depreciations, disposals and other information about the PPE to facilitate the reconciliation of any noted discrepancy between the records of the Accounting and the General Services Offices;
Facilitate the application of a one-time cleansing of PPE accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated          January 31, 2020; and
Consider increasing the number of personnel in the Accounting Office and in the MGSO to address the manpower constraints in the said Office and facilitate the maintenance of the required records.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:
Direct the MA to account properly for all land properties of the MGM using cost or fair value and effect the necessary adjustments in the books to arrive at a more reliable Land account balance in the FS;
Direct the Municipal Assessor to furnish the OMA with necessary documents for proper accounting of land properties recorded in the books of accounts and those owned and declared under the name of the MGM;
Allocate adequate budget for the titling of the subject land properties in the name of the MGM;
Evaluate the status of ownership of the 211 RPUs declared under the name of the MGM; and
Thereafter, facilitate the registration of the RPUs under the Torrens Title System as proof of absolute ownership by the MGM to safeguard the assets against third party claims, if applicable.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:
Instruct the MA and the MT to prioritize the reconciliation of the Cash in Bank accounts to come up with the correct balances in the FS;
Monitor the status of outstanding checks to prevent spoilage, in accordance with Section 59 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I;
Submit immediately the SB Resolutions, MOA and other documents authorizing the opening and maintenance of the three savings accounts, otherwise, transfer the balances to the GF and facilitate the closure thereof; and
Facilitate the closure of unnecessary bank accounts in accordance with Section 29 (3), Article VI of the 1987 Philippine Constitution and other relevant laws, rules and regulations.

Likewise, we recommended and the MA agreed to:
Exert utmost effort in the retrieval of prior years’ records in order to determine the nature and composition of the unidentified book reconciling items;
Take up all valid reconciling items by preparing JEVs duly supported with proper documentation and furnish the AT with copies of the same;
Revert the entries made for stale checks;
Prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries to take up the unrecorded savings accounts of the MGM, as well as the transactions thereof; and
Prepare and submit timely the BRS for all bank accounts of the MGM; and ensure that the submitted BRS are supported with the BS, DMs/CMs and other supporting schedules/documents.

Further, we recommended and the MTO agreed to:
Stop the practice of depositing collections to any bank accounts without legally specific and authorized purpose; and
Analyze the frequency of transactions per bank account, thereafter identify and recommend the closure of dormant bank accounts, if applicable.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Require the MTO to deposit promptly the trust collections to the concerned agencies;
Re-evaluate the non-moving unexpended balances of fund transfers received from various SAs and thereafter return the balances to them if still identifiable, or to the National Treasury;
Require the OMA to prepare the necessary adjusting entries to reclassify the balance of ₱378,248.82 to Trust Liabilities – DRRMF  account; and
Follow strictly the terms and conditions stipulated in the written agreement/undertaking.  Otherwise, obtain written authority from the SA to utilize the fund for purpose/s other than what is provided thereof.

We also reiterated our previous year’s audit recommendation and Management agreed to request for write-off of balances which remain dormant/non-moving accounts following the guidelines and procedures prescribed by COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended and Management agreed to strictly adhere to the relevant existing laws, rules and regulations on the utilization and disbursement of government funds by observing, among others, the following:
Direct the BAC and the Secretariat to strictly abide by the standards and requirements set forth by RA No. 9184, its 2016 Revised IRR and other relevant issuances on government procurement;
Require the Municipal Health Officer to use the latest PNF as guide in the procurement of medicines as well as in the day-to-day clinical decision-making to achieve better health outcomes;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursements are properly supported with the required documentation before payment to warrant their validity and propriety and to avoid future disallowance or suspension in audit; and
Furnish the Audit Team with advance copy of perfected contracts and POs together with the supporting documents and AIR for accepted deliveries in accordance with the requirements of COA Circular Nos. 2009-001 and 95-006, respectively.

We reiterated our prior years’ audit recommendation and Management agreed to strictly comply with DILG and DBM JMC No. 2017-1, by taking into consideration the following:
Develop a concrete plan that will articulate the PPA, timeline, expected deliverables for each phase, key milestones, etc.;
Adopt strategies to maximize the utilization of the 20 per cent Development Fund and implement the PPAs within the targeted timeframe to achieve the social, economic and environmental outcomes essential in the attainment of the constitutional objective of a desired quality of life for all;
Ensure that the 20 per cent Development Fund is used solely for development PPAs and no amount is utilized for expenditure items not allowed to be charged thereof as provided in DILG and DBM JMC No. 2017-1; and
Limit the obligations incurred within the available appropriations to avoid incurrence of budget deficit and possible disallowance in audit.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to issue demand letters to the accountable officers who are no longer connected with the Municipality, require them to liquidate all their outstanding advances;
Likewise, file a request for authority to write-off dormant accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 for long outstanding cash advances with less to no chance of being settled caused by death or whose whereabouts could no longer be traced; and
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to prioritize and increase the amount withheld from the salary and other money due from the AO with unliquidated CAs aged more than one year, so that the said balance will be settled on CY 2020.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. direct the Accountant to check whether the required documents are attached to the DVs before processing the same for approval and payment in compliance with Section 4 (6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445 and COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012;
b. direct all concerned employees to submit all the lacking documents listed in Appendix 1 as required in COA Circular No. 2012-001 for further review and evaluation of the Audit Team, otherwise a Notice of Suspension (NS) will be issued in accordance with the Rules and Regulations on Settlement of Accounts (RRSA).

a.	Direct the Municipal Accountant to issue Demand Letters to the concerned debtors/accountable officers for the liquidation of their accountabilities;


b.	Initiate collection measures to recover the aging accounts from persons liable who were already terminated from the government service or no longer connected with the Municipal Government; and

c.	Impose stricter control in the grant and liquidation of cash advances to ensure compliance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002.

Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to prioritize the reconciliation of the Cash in Bank accounts in order to come up with the correct balances of the said accounts as presented in the FS;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to take up the unrecorded deposits, disbursements and all valid reconciling items by preparing JEVs duly supported with proper documentation and furnish the Audit Team with copies of the same;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to conduct a thorough review of records to determine the validity of long outstanding deposits in transit and stale checks and make the necessary adjustments; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to submit timely the BRS together with the BS, DMs/CMs and supporting schedules/documents to COA for verification.

Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure proper accounting of the utilization of fund transfers received from NGAs through accurate recording of transactions and proper maintenance of SLs and supporting schedules;
Submit the liquidation reports promptly to SAs in accordance with the terms and conditions stipulated in the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) or the provisions under COA Circular No. 94-013, in case no reportorial requirements are provided in the MOA;
Re-evaluate the non-moving unexpended balances of fund transfers received from various NGAs and thereafter return the balances to the NGAs if still identifiable or make representations and obtain authority from them to utilize the unexpended balances for purposes other than what are provided in the MOA;
Request for write-off of balances which remain non-moving for 10 years or more and where settlement could no longer be ascertained, in accordance with the requirements of COA Circular No. 2016-005; and
Fast track the implementation of the projects related to fund transfers since the resources are readily available, and in order not to deprive the general public of the benefits that could be derived therefrom.

Direct the Municipal Treasurer and/or Supply Officer to conduct a physical count of all inventory items semestrally and render a report thereon within the prescribed period;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to properly account for the acquisition and issuance of the supplies and materials inventory based on IPSAS 12, Inventories, and make the necessary adjustments to reflect the correct balance of the affected inventory and expense accounts; and
Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to properly maintain and update the stock cards and SLCs, respectively, and reconcile their records regularly.

Direct the BAC, the Secretariat and the TWG to strictly abide by the standards set forth by RA No. 9184, its 2016 Revised IRR and other relevant issuances on government procurement;
Remind them also to exercise due diligence in the performance of their duties to ensure that all requirements of the procurement law are faithfully adhered to;
Require all members of the BAC, the Secretariat and the TWG to undergo relevant trainings on government procurement that will enhance their capabilities in discharging their respective functions in an effective and efficient manner; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer to comply with the requirements of COA Circular Nos. 2012-001 and 2013-004, respectively, at all times to avoid suspension or disallowance in audit.

Increase the bonding requirements of the SDO pursuant to Treasury Circular No. 02-2009 to protect the interest of the Municipality, otherwise ensure that cash advance granted is within the limit of his fidelity bond;
Require all the concerned AOs to settle their outstanding cash advances immediately by demanding the submission of liquidation reports and supporting documents. Otherwise, cause the withholding or suspension of their salaries for non-compliance therewith;
Strengthen the control measures to ensure timely submission of liquidation documents and full accounting of balances of cash advances by strictly monitoring the period of liquidation and impose sanctions on AOs who failed to liquidate on time; and
Strictly comply with the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 97-002 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.

We likewise recommended and Management agreed to require the Municipal Accountant to trace and review the entries made that resulted in the negative balances of cash advances and effect the necessary adjustment/s in the books in order to present the correct amount of cash advance accounts in the FS.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Treasurer’s Office (MTO) and the Office Municipal Accountant (OMA) concerned personnel to prioritize the reconciliation process and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly;

Require the OMA concerned personnel to maintain complete and updated PPE Ledger Cards to support GL account balances and the MTO concerned personnel to keep corresponding Property Cards for control purposes; 

Direct the Municipal Accountant to continue tracing back prior years’ acquisitions of PPE to have a complete detail of the PPE accounts so that the corresponding depreciation could be computed, to present fairly the carrying value of the depreciable PPE; and

Compel the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer with complete description and cost of road network projects to facilitate the preparation of Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant to perform periodic reconciliation of all Cash in Bank accounts pursuant to Section 3.2 of COA Circular No. 96-011, and immediately verify reconciling items to facilitate timely adjustments in the books of accounts;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to conduct a thorough review of records to determine the validity of all pending reconciling items and come up with the correct balances of the Cash in Bank accounts;

Investigate the cause/s of the negative balance in the SEF account and make the necessary adjustments in the books and consider the closure of dormant accounts to avoid unnecessary charges; and

Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to exert utmost effort to reconcile their records on a regular basis to support the correctness of the Cash in Bank account balances in the financial statements (FS).

We recommended that Management institute measures to further improve the financial performance of the market operations by increasing revenue collections through, but not limited to, the following:

Enhance the existing collection strategy of the MTO to ensure the prompt payment of market dues by the stallholders;



Send out demand letters to all delinquent occupants to settle immediately their unpaid market dues. Otherwise, impose the sanctions provided under the Market Code; 

Consider offering the idle or inactive market stalls to interested individuals/businesses to maximize the income generation potential of the said stalls; and



Execute a contract of lease between the stallholder to set forth the terms, conditions, rights and responsibilities for the use of market stall.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:

Conduct a detailed review and analysis of the inter-agency payable accounts, including confirmation with the respective government agencies, to determine the correct balances of the said accounts and thereafter, effect the necessary adjustments/corrections in the books;

Investigate the causes of discrepancy in the amounts transferred in the Due to BIR account under the GF and the SEF as against the amounts reflected in the TF so that necessary adjustments can be effected; 
Cause the immediate remittance of amounts withheld to the concerned government agencies and ensure that monthly remittances correspond to the exact amounts withheld to avoid abnormal balances in the payable accounts;

Ensure the timely recording and posting of transactions pertaining to these payables in the SL and ensure that the totals of the SL balances reconcile with the respective GL balance; and

Strengthen internal accounting control on the monitoring and review of withheld amounts payable to government agencies including government contributions.

We recommended that Management strictly comply with the Disaster Preparedness Minimum Standards developed by the Local Government Academy of the DILG and Department of Education-Department of Social Welfare and Development-DILG-Department of Health (DOH) JMC No. 1, Series of 2013, by taking into consideration the following: 

Assign Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Office (MDRRMO) personnel for DRRM Administration and Training that shall perform DRRM functions provided in Section 7 of National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council-DILG-DBM-Civil Service Commission (CSC) Memorandum Circular No. 2014-001;

Equip the MDRRMO personnel and volunteer with necessary trainings that will help them in the efficient and effective management of DRRM-related projects and activities;

Organize an Evacuation Center Management Committee (ECMC) that will be tasked to prepare the ECM Plan for the Municipality and coordinate the delivery of necessary assistance and services to the evacuees; 

Allocate funds in its Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management (LDRRM) budget for the construction of additional evacuation centers to address the shortage; and

Require the Social Welfare and Development Office (SWDO) to be in the frontline of service delivery during and in the aftermath of man-made and natural disasters and calamities, particularly in the disposition and utilization of relief goods.

We recommended that Management:

Expedite the revision of its 10-year Municipal Solid Waste Management (SWM) Plan (2017 - 2026) and submit the same to the Department of Environment and Natural Resources - Environmental Management Bureau for final approval of the National Solid Waste Management Committee;
Strictly comply with the requirements of RA No. 9003 particularly on the efficient collection, proper transfer and transport of wastes; and efficient management of residuals and of final disposal sites and/or any other related technologies for the destruction/reuse of residuals;

Prioritize SWM programs and projects by providing/allocating enough budget for their full implementation to address all the identified key issues as discussed in the Municipal SWM plan;

Encourage the remaining 22 barangays to establish their own Materials Recovery Facilities (MRFs) for the collection, segregation, recycling of biodegradable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes; and

Provide adequate assistance in restoring the two not functional barangay MRFs to functional status.

We further recommended that Management consider filling up the Ecosystem and Environmental Resource Management Section Officer position who will be in the frontline of the delivery of services concerning the environment and natural resources.

We recommended Management to:

a. Fast-track the implementation of projects and ensure the conduct of a thorough study prior to preparation of programs and projects under the 20% Development Fund to avoid disagreements between the Executive and Legislative bodies;

b. Facilitate the procurement and implementation of projects to ensure that constituents could benefit from said projects.

We recommended and Management committed to:
a.  Continue with the Information Education Campaign (IEC) and cooperate with the barangays and other sectors of the society for the proper implementation of waste segregation according to waste classification;

b.  Instruct all garbage collectors to properly collect segregated garbage according to compostable and recyclable waste materials;

c.  Monitor and facilitate the establishment of Material Recovery Facilities of each barangay as required in Section 32 of RA 9003 for an efficient and effective collection and disposal of solid waste that will provide as an additional measure to mitigate health and environmental risks; and
d.  Strictly implement the Municipality’s Solid Waste Management Plan, most specially, the proper segregation and collection of solid waste to reduce the volume of garbage disposal at dumping sites in compliance to the abovementioned Act.

