CY 2016 AAR We recommended that the Municipal Mayor consider the following courses of actions:
1. advise the OIC- Waterworks System Supervisor to update the computerized system so it could generate the balance of Accounts Receivable for a given period; 
2. Advise the Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary adjusting entry (Dr.) Revenue 1,430,025.50 (Cr.) Government Equity Account 1,430,025.50

We recommended that Management:
a. Create an Inventory Committee that will conduct annual inventory of all the properties of the LGU noting down the location, persons accountable and the physical condition of the property. The committee shall prepare and certify correct the RPCPPE based on actual inventory taking of each office and submit a copy to COA;
b. Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain- complete and updated PPE ledger cards to support GL account balances and the Supply Officer/Municipal Treasurer to keep corresponding property cards for control _purposes. These records shall contain adequate details/description of the properties such as model, serial number, location, cost and other information necessary to facilitate its identification;
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant to continue exerting efforts in tracing back prior years’ acquisitions of Property, Plant and -and-Equipment-to-have-a-complete-detail-of the fixed assets accounts so that the corresponding  depreciation could be computed, to present fairly the true value of the depreciable fixed asset accounts; and
d. Compel the Municipal Treasurer to determine the officials/employees to whom the equipment were issued and issue the corresponding Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) for each property to pinpoint the person accountable and responsible thereon. Moreover, renew all ARE every three years for the signature of the current holder of each item listed in the PPE accounts.

We reiterated our prior years’ audit -recommendations-that-Management:
a. Require the concerned officers and employees to liquidate/settle immediately their outstanding cash advances by demanding the immediate submission of duly accomplished liquidation reports. Otherwise, withhold any money due them;
b. strengthen  the  operation  of preventive and monitoring controls to ensure timely submission of liquidation documents and full accounting of balances of cash advances by monitoring strictly the period of liquidating cash advances;
c. Exert extra effort to locate the whereabouts of accountable officers who are no longer in the service and issue final demand letters; and
d. Comply strictly with the provision of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.
We  likewise recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to trace the entries made that resulted in the negative balances of the cash advance balances and effect the necessary adjusting—entries—in—the—agency—books—i order to present the correct amount of the Cash Advances accounts in the financial statements; and make appropriate action to those who did not liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period or render account of their accountabilities after demand pursuant to CSC Memorandum Circular No. 12,s. 2012.

We recommend that Management require the:
a. Municipal Treasurer to prepare the certified list of real property tax and special education taxes due and collectible based on the Real Property Tax  Account Register/Taxpayer’s index card and submit this—to—the—Municipal-Accountant—at—the—beginning of each year to set up the receivables;
b. Municipal Accountant to set up the receivables based on the list submitted by the MTO;
c. Municipal Accountant and Treasurer reconcile their records with the Municipal Assessor to come up with an accurate real property tax receivable.
